Data:

BPRS <- read.csv("BPRSL")
RATS <- read.csv("RATSL")

The RATS dataset:

DT::datatable(RATS, options = list(pageLength = 10))

The above data studies the temporal trends in the weight of rats, taking repeated measurements from each week, group and individual. These variables could potentially contribute to correlations between individual weights.

Graphical Representation

RATS$timef <- factor(RATS$Time)
RATS$group <- factor(RATS$Group)
p <- ggplot(data = RATS, aes(x = timef, y = Weight)) + geom_boxplot() + geom_jitter(aes(col = group)) + xlab("Time (days") + ylab("Weight (g)")
p

The above plot indicates weight ranging from approximately 200 g to 500 g for the rats on day 1, which increased to approximately 300 g - 650 g by day 64. Group 1 had the lowest weights throughout the study.

Taking a closer look at each treatment:

p2 <- ggplot(data = RATS, aes(x = timef, y = Weight)) + geom_point(aes(col = group)) + xlab("Time (days)") + ylab("Weight (g)")
  
 p2 <- p2 + facet_wrap(~group)
 p2

There are quite some variations in Group 2. Wonder if these are contributed by the same individual. Let’s take a yet closer look at this group.

RATS$individual <- factor(RATS$ID)

p3 <- ggplot(data = RATS, aes(x = timef, y = Weight)) + geom_point(aes(col = individual)) + xlab("Time (days)") + ylab("Weight (g)")

p3 <- p3 + facet_wrap(~group)
 p3

As suspected, the variation is contributed to by one individual, ID 12.

From the above graphs, it appears that time and group may have a significant influence on the weight of the individuals. The individuals themselves may present some variations, and these may need to be accounted for (especially ID 12).

We’ll try to see if our hypothesis is correct, using ANOVA.

#let's create a summary dataset first
RATS.s <- RATS %>%            
  filter(ID != 12) %>%                   #We'll remove ID 12, which is causing a lot of variation within Group 2
  group_by(Group, ID) %>%
  summarise( mean=mean(Weight) ) %>%
  ungroup()
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'Group'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
glimpse(RATS.s)
## Rows: 15
## Columns: 3

Let’s take a look at whether the graphical representation of the summarised data indicates any considerable differences in rat weights between groups.

RATS.s$group = factor(RATS.s$Group)
ggplot(RATS.s, aes(x = group, y = mean)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  stat_summary(fun = "mean", geom = "point", shape=23, size=4, fill = "white") +
  scale_y_continuous(name = "Mean weight")

It looks like the mean weights may vary significantly between the three groups.

exploring the data graphically:

library(ggplot2)
p4 <- ggplot(data = BPRS, aes(x = week.f, y = bprs)) + geom_point(aes(col = treatment.f)) + xlab("Time (weeks)") + ylab("BPRS")

p4 <- p4 + facet_wrap(~treatment.f)
 p4

Hmmm…. Not sure if treatment has a significant effect or not. Let’s try visualizing with a boxplot, maybe?

p5 <- ggplot(data = BPRS, aes(x = week.f, y = bprs)) + geom_boxplot(aes(col = treatment.f)) + xlab("Time (weeks)") + ylab("BPRS")


 p5

The value of BPRS seems to be higher in treatment 2 in 5 out of 9 weeks. Either way, the value does decrease with each progressing week, so we may have a significant effect there.

Let’s see what a linear regression can tell us about this.

lm.BPRS1<- lm(bprs~week, data = BPRS)

Let’s give mixed modeling a try now

library(lme4)
## Loading required package: Matrix
## 
## Attaching package: 'Matrix'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:tidyr':
## 
##     expand, pack, unpack
library(performance)

# Create a random intercept model
lmm.BPRS1 <- lmer(bprs ~ week + treatment + (1 | subject), data = BPRS, REML = FALSE)
summary(lmm.BPRS1)

As indicated by the “performance” function, the fixed effects (week and treatment) explain 18.6% of the variations in bprs (as indicated by marginal R2. But with the random effect, “subject”, as well, the model explains 44% of the variation (Conditional R2).

Let’s try another model without the treatment as a fixed effect.

lmm.BPRS2 <- lmer(bprs ~ week +  (treatment | subject), data = BPRS, REML = FALSE)

In both these models, the week does not appear to have a significant effect on the bprs.However, the chi2 value of the second model is significant.
